Entered observation @ 1935. Mother stated to this nurse @ 1950, that daughter felt "light-headed". Water was given. @ 1954, patient started to gag. Went to restroom. @ 1958, she was walked with this nurse and others to "bed" that's located in vaccination clinic. Mother explained to this nurse and others that her daughter shows s/s of these symptoms upon each vaccination. Lightheadedness and nausea lasted for about 10-15 minutes. Cold compress was applied to help relieve s/s from vaccine. States she felt better around 2005. Left observation @ 2005, showed no s/s of distress.
16 2021-01-24 vomiting, nausea Nausea causing vomiting 15 hours after injection
16 2021-02-18 nausea Went to sit down and passed out; felt dizzy; nausious/nausia; sweaty; sick feeling; as she was ghost... Read more
Close
Went to sit down and passed out; felt dizzy; nausious/nausia; sweaty; sick feeling; as she was ghost white; bad headache.; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable other Health Professional reported for herself. A 16-year-old female patient received the second dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, lot number: EN5318) via intramuscular on left arm on 02Feb2021 03:45 PM, at age of 16 years old at single dose for Covid-19 immunization. Patient was not pregnant at the time of vaccination. Medical history reported as allergies to medications, food, or other products was reported as none known. Prior to vaccination, patient was not diagnosed with COVID-19. Other medications the patient received within 2 weeks of vaccination included multivitamin and melatonin gummies. The patient previously received the first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, lot number: EL3248), via intramuscular at left arm on 12Jan2021 03:45 PM for Covid-19 immunization. The patient did not receive any other vaccines within 4 weeks prior to the COVID vaccine. It was reported morning after vaccine 03Feb2021 08:00 patient was felt dizzy and nausious. Told her mom and her mom ran over as she was ghost white. Went to sit down and passed out. Patient experienced sweaty, nausia, sick feeling and bad headache. Patient went to the emergency room (ER), they gave fluids and blood work. No heart issues noted. Felt better around 3 hours after. Headache was bad and continued on 05Feb2021 (reported today). Also, still feel nausious and had to lay down. All events occurred on 03Feb2021 08:00 AM. Patient was recovering. It was reported the adverse event result in emergency room/department or urgent care. The seriousness criteria were reported as not serious, no results in death, no life threatening, no caused/prolonged hospitalization, no disabling/incapacitating, no congenital anomaly/birth defect. Patient was received treatment for the adverse event included fluids and heart monitoring. The patient underwent lab tests and procedures which included blood work in Feb2021. Since the vaccination, patient had not been tested for COVID-19. Outcome of events bad headache and nauseous was not recovered, for felt dizzy, as she was ghost white, passed out, sweaty, sick feeling was recovering.; Sender's Comments: Based on the information provided and plausible temporal association, a contributory of the suspect drug to the reported events cannot be completely excluded. Case will be reassessed when additional information is available. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer drug is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees and Investigators, as appropriate.

The child was administered the vaccine at about 11:15 a.m on 2/7/2021. She woke up about 14 hours later with vaccine side effects the family was prepared for, including headache, chills, nausea, vomiting and fatigue. This all resolved within 48 hours. Approximately one week later, the child woke up again in the night with severe chills in the middle of the night. It was a sudden onset following a week of feeling well. She had to sit in a warm/hot shower for an hour to get warm. She described it as "freezing to death." She has never experienced anything like this before.

I was alerted by the pharmacy technician I was needed outside of the immunization room and patient had vomited. It seemed to be mostly stomach acid (no food particles) and was roughly 12oz or less of fluid (hard to tell since it was contained in a plastic bag. Patient sipped on some water, which she tolerated well. She stated she suddenly felt really dizzy and then felt the need to throw up. After the water, she felt better and was looking to see if eating something would help settle her stomach. She did not appear pale or diaphoretic. I encouraged her to stay longer for continued observation by she left before 15 minutes were up after the vomiting. She was in the pharmacy observation area for about 20 minutes total. She smiled and waved as she left.

16 2021-04-04 vomiting Pfizer 1st dose administered at COVID-19 Clinic. Client reported being diagnosed with COVID-19 durin... Read more
Close
Pfizer 1st dose administered at COVID-19 Clinic. Client reported being diagnosed with COVID-19 during the last week of September 2020. Reviewed with client what to expect with side effects after receiving 1st dose. No questions or concerns voiced. Gave vaccine at 1505. Mother then stated after vaccine administered that client has history of syncopal episodes after vaccines. Provided water to client and recommended for client to be moved to a supine position. Client declined lying down. About 1506, client lost consciousness for 4 seconds. Client returned to consciousness without intervention and was alert and oriented x 4. Client had 10mL emesis after returning to consciousness. Recommended for client to lie down, client declined. Provided graham crackers and cycling floor fan. Client able to tolerate water and graham crackers. After 5 minutes, client stated feeling better. Mother elaborated that about 1 year ago had first vagal response to needles when having wisdom teeth removed. Happened again during IV initiation for tonsillectomy surgery and during flu vaccination 2020. Monitored client in clinic room for 20 minutes, no further reaction. Advised for client to state needing to lie down when returns for 2nd dose. Client and mother verbalize understanding. Mother escorted client from clinic to private vehicle.

16 2021-04-08 nausea Patient received first dose of Pfizer covid-19 vaccine on 4/9/2021 at 1800 with her mother in attend... Read more
Close
Patient received first dose of Pfizer covid-19 vaccine on 4/9/2021 at 1800 with her mother in attendance after consent was acquired. At 1805 patient began to feel hot and nauseous. The patient thought she was going to vomit, so she left her chair in the waiting area to head to the restroom at the back of the store. at 1807, Upon rising the patient became weak in the knees and began to collapse. The patient's mother initially supported the patient and I was called to assist the patient to the floor. The patient was very pale in appearance as she was assisted gently to the floor, avoiding any injury. EMS was called shortly after the event around 1810. The patient remained conscious however was a bit disoriented initially while lying on the floor. The patient recovered quickly, however remained nauseous and complained of feeling hot. Upon questioning the patient, she had not eaten since lunch at school at 1300. The patient was given a cold water and a sprite, of which she had a couple of drinks out of each. The patient was relocated back into a chair at 1815 as she was feeling much better. EMS arrived at 1821. EMS performed a general assessment and a blood pressure check resulting in 130/80. The patient's mother dismissed any further treatment from EMS. EMS exited the building at 1827. The patient and mother waited in the store for a while longer. Both patient and mother exited on their own, denying escort from associates at 1840.

On day 2 (4/3/21) in the morning she felt well, but later that afternoon she had severe abdominal pain. She had resolution of symptoms after 15 minutes, but recurred about 1-2 hours later with vomiting and abdominal pain. Mom reports her pain was crippling, doubled over and on the floor due to pain. Took to urgent care for evaluation. UA and UPT negative. ED records show abdominal exam was normal except for "increased peristalsis". Treated with Zofran with resolution of vomiting. discharged home. Abdominal pain self-limited and resolved without further intervention within a few hours.

Concomitant mediations included ethinylestradiol/levonorgestrel (JOLESSA) taken "to decrease her periods" from 2019 ("about two years ago") and ongoing and at an unspecified dose, cyclic, for three months straight with no placebo. Then takes a placebo pill for one week straight and biotin taken "for hair and nail growth" from an unspecified date ("she began taking within the last 6 months") and ongoing. There was no history of previous immunization with the Pfizer vaccine, there were no additional vaccines administered on the same date as the COVID-19 vaccine and there were no prior vaccinations within 4 weeks. It was not provided whether there were adverse events following prior vaccinations. On 07Apr2021 the patient experienced began having left eye twitches and they progressed to spasms and the nose and left side of her face. It then included both sides of her face, patient could not open her eye or control her face, her left leg had goosebumps and chills, pinching in her left shoulder, nausea and headache. The reporter called to report that her daughter had a severe reaction to the first dose of the COVID-19 vaccine. The clinical course was reported as follows: The patient received the first dose of the COVID-19 vaccine in her left arm. Less than an hour after receiving the COVID-19 vaccine, the patient developed goosebumps and chills in her left leg. The reporter was not very concerned about it at the time. About 9:00PM that same night, the patient started complaining of pinching in her left shoulder. The reporter was not too terribly concerned. By 9:30PM, that same night, the patient started to have left eye twitches. Then they increased to eye spasms, then the patient could not open her eye or control her face. Then, it progressed to patients nose and left side of her face. At that point, the reporter tried to contact a nurse with the health insurance advice line. She waited for 30 minutes. The patient's symptoms continued to get worse, so the reporter took the patient to the emergency room. While the patient was in the emergency room triage, while hospital staff were getting her blood pressure and temperature, her symptoms also started to involve the right side of her face. Around 10:15PM, that same night, the patient started to get nauseous and a headache kicked in. The emergency department took patient straight back to a room. The patient was not admitted to the hospital. The emergency department started an IV on the patient, and they administered Reglan, Benadryl, and Toradol to treat her symptoms. The emergency department ran blood tests, preformed a urinalysis and a CT scan. The reporter did not know what all blood testing that was done revealed; however, the reporter did know that they told her that none of the testing revealed anything and were all normal. The patient was eventually discharged from the emergency department at about 1:50AM. She was sent home with Butalbital, for headache and was advised to take ibuprofen. She was still having the twitching but not as bad when discharged. On 08Apr2021, the patient's symptoms had not completely subsided, but were significantly better. On 08Apr2021, the patient woke up with nausea, chills and a headache. The reporter expected the patient to have these side effects. The side effects continued until very late in the day on 10Apr2021. The patient never vomited, was only very nauseous. The reporter also stated that when the woman was administering the first dose of the COVID-19 vaccine, the woman said "oops" and it was not explained what "oops" meant. The reporter asked if it was possible that the patient received the dose subcutaneously and that was why she had these side effects. The reporter also stated that the second dose was scheduled for 28Apr2021 and she asked if the patient should receive the second dose. The clinical outcomes of the events began having left eye twitches and they progressed to spasms and the nose and left side of her face. It then included both sides of her face, patient could not open her eye or control her face, her left leg had goosebumps and chills, pinching in her left shoulder, nausea and headache all recovered/resolved on 10Apr2021. No follow-up attempts are needed; No further information is expected.

vomited; nauseous; visibly distressed; hyperventilating; began seizing/visibly having tonic clonic seizure; HR 116/ HR 114; HR 56; RR 30; BP of 141/46; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable nurse. An 18-year-old female patient received the first dose of BNT162B2 (Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 vaccine, lot number: EW0170), intramuscular, administered in the right arm on 20Apr2021 at 12:45 as a single dose for COVID-19 immunization. Medical history included anxiety from an unknown date and unknown if ongoing. Concomitant medications included fluoxetine hydrochloride (PROZAC) taken for an unspecified indication, start and stop date were not reported. The patient did not have COVID prior to the vaccination. The patient did not receive other vaccines in four weeks. The patient had not been tested for COVID post vaccination. On 20Apr2021 at 12:45, the patient and her father moved into the waiting area with vehicle. According to the patient's dad, the patient began seizing in the car one minute after the vaccine administration. The dad called out to waiting area monitor. At 12:57 the patient was visibly having tonic clonic seizure and was administered with EpiPen in the right Leg. 911 was called. The patient stopped seizing and was awake and confused. She then became AOx4 (oriented to four spheres; time/place/person/situation). The patient visibly distressed and hyperventilating. At 12:59 the patient had tonic clonic movements and seizure again. The seizure lasted less than 15 seconds. The patient then became AOx4 again, distressed, and became nauseous. Heart rate (HR) was 56 and SpO2 was 98%. At 13:00 the patient vomited while sitting up. The patient was still distressed and hyperventilating with respiratory rate (RR) of 30. The patient's post vomiting HR was 116 and SpO2 was 97%. The patient moved to a stretcher and moved to the shade. At 13:06 firefighters arrived and the patient had an HR of 114, BP of 141/46, SpO2 of 97%, RR 24 and AOx4. At 13:12 the ambulance arrived and the patient was taken to (Place). The events resulted in a visit to the Emergency room/department or urgent care. The outcome of the events was unknown.; Sender's Comments: Based on the available information, and on close temporal association, a reasonable possibility cannot be excluded that the suspect drug BNT162B2 (Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 vaccine) contributed to the occurrence of the serious event Generalised tonic-clonic seizure. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees and Investigators, as appropriate.

Medical history included seasonal allergies from an unknown date. The patient did not receive any other vaccines within 4 weeks prior to the COVID vaccine. Prior to vaccination, the patient was not diagnosed with COVID-19. Since the vaccination, it was unknown if the patient has been tested for COVID-19. Concomitant medication included fluoxetine 60 mg taken for an unspecified indication, and an unspecified oral contraceptive. It was reported that on 23Mar2021, the patient received Pfizer Covid vaccine and felt a little dizzy on 11:00. She also started noting mumbling, slurred speech, passed out for about 15 (unspecified) after using the bathroom, developed a "static" feeling in her head and then noted her left eye shutting and then weakness in her left arm and leg. The adverse events result in Doctor or other healthcare professional office/clinic visit and Emergency room/department or urgent care. No treatment was received for the adverse events. The outcome of the event nausea was recovered in Mar2021, and for other events was recovered on 23Mar2021 20:30. Information about lot/batch number was requested.; Sender's Comments: Based on the information currently available and temporal association, a possible causal relationship cannot be excluded between the suspect product BNT162B2 and the reported event Passed out. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics Committees, and Investigators, as appropriate.

The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. The patient historical vaccines included: flu vaccine in mid-Nov2020 and first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE, Lot Number: EK5730, Expiration Date: Unknown) via intramuscular route of administration in left upper arm on 28Dec2020 09:20 at single dose for covid-19 immunization. The patient had Injection site pain, Flu-like symptoms (clarified as flu minus vomiting), Headache, GI symptoms, Weakness, Fever, Muscle fatigue and leg shakiness with the first dose. There were no other vaccines administered within four weeks. On 18Jan2021 she experienced more interesting side effects. She had injection site pain the afternoon of 18Jan2021 by 20:00 that night (18Jan2021), she had laid down in bed, and she felt like she was being stung by wasps at the COVID-19 Vaccine injection site. The injection site pain was not bad but the pain was constant and by the second day the injection site pain had faded. The bad injection site pain clarifying the injection site pain was a burning sensation. She said if she puts her hand on the vaccine injection site now, she can still feel a burning sensation. She said there is not swelling or redness at the vaccine injection site. She said she developed extremely swollen left axillary lymph nodes after her second COVID-19 Vaccine dose. She said the left axillary lymph node swelling was so extreme it inhibited her left arm movement. She said she developed numbness and tingling in her left elbow and left wrist as well. She said the left axillary lymph node swelling has gone down, so the swollen lymph nodes are not impeding her left arm movement now. She said the left axillary lymph node remains swollen enough that her bra hits the swollen lymph node, making the left axillary lymph nodes painful. She said the numbness and tingling in her left elbow and left wrist is less frequent, but not gone. She said her side effects after the second COVID-19 Vaccine didn't improve for probably 4-5 days after they developed. She said the left axillary lymph node swelling has improved marginally, and the vaccine injection site burning sensation is less, but the left elbow and left wrist numbness and tingling is persistent. On 23Jan2021 or 24Jan2021 she developed fatigue, persistent diarrhea, weakness, headache, and very mild chills and muscle aches. She said she had no fever. Her symptoms lasted 2 days and then completely resolved on Jan2021. She said her left elbow and left wrist numbness and tingling is persisting. The patient experienced difficulty breathing, chills, fluctuating fever, nausea, dizziness, weakness, fast heartbeat, tiredness, loss of taste and smell, muscle pain, injection site pain, anxiety, cough, sore throat, nasal drip, crying, extreme fatigue, Etc on 31Dec2020 at 06:00 PM. The events resulted in doctor or other healthcare professional office/clinic visit, emergency. The patient was hospitalized for 1 day and received treatment included blood thinner rivaroxaban (XARELTO) and had 2 weeks quarantine. The patient had Covid prior to vaccination and tested positive for Covid test post vaccination on 01Jan2021. The outcome of the events was not resolved. Information on Lot/batch number has been requested.; Sender's Comments: Based on available information, a possible contributory role of the subject product, BNT162B2 vaccine, cannot be excluded for the suspected LOE, SARS-CoV-2 test positive and the other reported events due to temporal relationship. Of note, it is reported that the patient had history of COVID 19 infection prior to the vaccination. There is limited information provided in this report. Additional information is needed to better assess the case, including complete medical history, diagnostics, counteractive treatment measures and concomitant medications. This case will be reassessed once additional information is available. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. I fell asleep for about 20 minutes around 12, and when I woke up I felt a little less nauseous and headache-y. I stayed in bed for an hour, and I ate some pudding over the course of an hour or two, but I thinking about eating much else made me feel nauseous. right sided numbness; severe headache; nausea; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable nurse, reporting for herself. A 22-year-old non-pregnant female patient received the first dose of the bnt162b2 (BNT162B2; Lot Number: EK4176), via an unspecified route of administration in the left arm on 15Jan2021 at 09:00 at a single dose for covid-19 immunization. The patient received the immunization in a hospital. Medical history included Ehlers-Danlos, allergic asthma, and fracture. Concomitant medication included drospirenone/ethinylestradiol (NIKKI) for birth control. There were no other vaccines given in four weeks. The patient previously took tramadol (MANUFACTURER UNKNOWN) and experienced allergies. On 28Jan2021 at 11:00, the patient experienced right sided numbness, severe headache, and nausea, which were serious for disability. Therapeutic measures were taken as a result of the events. The patient was treated in the emergency room and sent home with TIA protocol to follow with neurologist. There was no COVID prior or post vaccination. The clinical outcome of the events was not recovered. No follow-up attempts are needed. No further information is expected.; Sender's Comments: Based on the information currently available the causal association between the reported events right sided numbness, severe headache, and nausea and the usage of the vaccine BNT162B2 cannot be excluded but also the contributory role of the concomitant medications/medical history of the patient need to be taken into consideration. The case will be reassessed should the additional information be available. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to regulatory authorities, Ethics Committees, and Investigators, as appropriate.

This patient called employee health and asked if symptoms lasting over 48 hours were ordinary or if she should be tested for COVID-19. Employee health informed patient to get tested in case of exposure. Patient was negative, however remained nauseous and had low grade fevers and aches. Patient applied hydrocortisone cream and took Benadryl. As of today, 1/27, patient is afebrile, not nauseous, and rash has disappeared.

For concomitant medications, the patient did not receive any other vaccines within 4 weeks prior to the COVID vaccine. After receiving the vaccine, the patient was sitting in the observation area for about 10 minutes when she started to feel dizzy and nauseous. She raised her hand up and called for the nurse to come over. She passed out. She was pulseless for 30 seconds and they had to begin giving her CPR chest compressions. She woke up lying on the ground and was taken to the emergency room (ER) where they ran tests to see how she was doing and for observation for several hours. The patient was "discharged" this afternoon and was doing better. The events result in emergency room/department or urgent care. Treatment was received for the events, ER observation and care, and CPR chest compressions. The patient underwent lab tests and procedures which included test on 22Jan2021: unknown results. The outcome of events at the time of last observation was recovering. The reporter's assessment of the events was non-serious, no results in death, no life threatening, not causing/prolonging hospitalization, no disabling/incapacitating, no congenital anomaly/birth defect. Information on the lot/batch number has been requested.; Sender's Comments: The reported passed out and pulseless for 30 seconds were likely related to the first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE) due to temporal relationship. However, considering the clinical course and medical history, other cause(s)/confounding factors cannot be excluded. The case will be reassessed should additional information become available. The impact of this report on the benefit/risk profile of the Pfizer product is evaluated as part of Pfizer procedures for safety evaluation, including the review and analysis of aggregate data for adverse events. Any safety concern identified as part of this review, as well as any appropriate action in response, will be promptly notified to Regulatory Authorities, Ethics committees and Investigators, as appropriate.

Close
I received my first shot on April 6th, 2021, and on April 18th, 2021 I experienced extreme numbness with slight pain in the fold and shoulder of my arm. I went to the ER and they took a cat scan of my neck and reported back that everything looked normal - the nurse said it was most likely Cervical Radiculopathy. Then the following morning around 11 AM, I experienced very intense burning in my chest starting on the right side, eventually moving to the left encompassing my entire upper chest. I also experienced a very bad migraine, which I am typically used to but this one was more of a pressure headache between my temples that I felt in my ears and jaw. I made the decision to go back to the ER and to a different one this time. The ER failed to administer a Covid-19 test and to take bloodwork - both faults that family and friends in the medical field have pointed out to me. The doctor there had me receive an IV, a chest X-Ray, and an EKG. The X-Ray and EKG were both normal. The doctor had ordered a Covid-19 test but the nurse forgot to administer it before my discharge. In my IV I received Benadryl and Reglan along with typical IV fluids. I was also given Pepcid and Mylanta. At the end of my visit, the doctor concluded that he thought it was my acid reflux acting up - gastroenteritis. I went home and continued to experience chest burning, tightness, occasional numbness/pains in my body, and very, very bad headaches. On top of that, I could barely swallow - it felt as if my throat was closing. I took Pepcid and Tums and neither really did anything. After seeing a Cardiologist this same week, they ordered an Echocardiogram and routine bloodwork (metabolic panel). I will also be following up with a GI, and I received a Covid-19 test today and am awaiting the results. It is possible I contracted Covid before my shot, but it is also possible that I am having a delayed reaction to my first vaccination as well. Who knows.

Aside from the usual chills, body aches, etc, I ended up calling my doctor over a separate concerning issue - very high heart rate. I woke up at 8am the day after getting my 2nd Pfizer dose, walked to use the restroom, walked back to bed, and laid back down. Within a couple minutes I noticed my heart felt like it was racing and I was out of breath as if I had just come back from a jog, not a trip to the restroom. Heart rate continued fluctuating from 105-115bpm just laying in bed. Was also feeling fatigued, nauseous, dizzy when standing up, and with slight difficulty breathing. Called advice nurse after 30min of no change. They had me check heart rate manually (had been going off FitBit), and timing was consistent with what FitBit was reading . Nurse advised to keep resting and drink lots of water, scheduled follow-up with a Doctor later in the morning. It should be noted that I had been alternating between water and Pedialyte constantly all day, starting 5/17 through when this happened (and then the next few days as well), so I should not have been dehydrated. Follow-up call with Dr. (on-call Dr., not my usual one) was scheduled for 11:45am, and by then all concerning heart symptoms had passed. The Dr. basically reiterated what the nurse had told me, in keeping up with fluids. And that sometimes temperature change, even if you don't completely get a fever, can cause a high heart rate. As more information is coming out regarding younger people developing myocarditis after the mRNA vaccines however, I wanted to mention this in case it could possibly be related.
